    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "right, so it's basically a tiny invisible war going on. if i wanted to test for that, would i need to look at the pH levels or something? i'm just trying to figure out if there's some kind of \"unseen\" factor out there that's sabotaging the dough's growth even when i follow the rules.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Testing the pH is a good starting point, as the lactic acid bacteria are the main culprits for lowering the pH, which affects the environment for the yeast. If the pH swings wildly or stays too low for too long, it suggests the acid production is unbalanced.\n\nHowever, just looking at pH is only half the battle, and you need to watch the *activity* too. You could try a simple observation test: look at the texture and the rate of rise over several feedings. If one feeding produces a huge, fast burst of activity followed by a sluggish period, that's a telltale sign of a microbial imbalance. Sometimes, a little bit of a different, tougher microbe—maybe a stray fungus or some stubborn, slow-moving mold—can sneak in and hog the resources.",
      "source": "target",
